  title: Why use default instead of specifying a literal value like 0 or null?
  text: 'Using default makes your code more maintainable and less error-prone. It
    automatically adapts if the type of the variable changes. For example, if you
    change a variable from int to float, default will still provide the correct zero-equivalent
    value without needing to change your code.

    However when you don''t want
    a zero-equivalent value it''s perfectly fine to use any value you define yourself,
    like -1 on an int to represent some invalid value.'
